@NODE Themethod "The Method - How does it actually work ?"



 * The Method:
 =============


  Basically, all I've done is use the custom copper creation commands
 that Amos already offers, to build up either a 320*256 or a 640*256
 256 colour screen.   




 *  The OPEN_SCREEN subroutine firstly open's TWO normal Amos screens,
    screen 0 and screen 1, both are same size and depth.

    E.g. 640,256,16,hires.

    Two standard Amos screens are needed so that we can both use our
    regular Amos drawing commands on them (for the moment) and since Amos
    rejects open screen requests for 256 colours directly.... ;)


 *  Next we need to find the physical locations of each bitplane in 
    memory of two screens and store them in an array for later use..


 *  Now we read the palette information into the array creatively titled
    PALCOLOUR.  This array hold the R,G,B data of the 256 unique colours.


 *  Next we create our custom copper.  Firstly we switch the Amos copper
    system off, then we init our custom copper routine.


 *  The custom copper routine builds a fairly basic copper list.


    The copper now includes some limited support for hardware sprites
    although, you'll really need to know how to program sprites at
    a hardware level to really get a great deal of use out of them.



 NOTE: I'm not going to explain how to construct a copper, I'll assume 
       you already understand how to do this... ;)



 *  After the copper list is defined, it's time to init it's pointers to
    our previously opened screens (0 & 1) and  Hardware Sprite
    information (bank 14).

    The init bitplane routine uses the actual pointers to each of the
    combined 8 bitplanes and then moves them into our copper list.

    With screen 0 becoming the lower 4 planes or bits (planes 0,1,2,3)
    and screen 2 becoming the higher planes / bits, planes 4,5,6,7

    Note: Unfortunately hardware sprite support is very limited in this
          version of AmosAGA. Sorry
   

 *  Next, here comes the only real 'hack' in this example, which simply
    replaces one of the copper commands (which I've defined as a dummy
    or a padding command) with a different one, via poking directly into
    the copper list, just as our bitplane init routine did above.

    The reason this is needed, is that Amos didn't want to allow me to
    do a 'cop move $1fc,$1001' as it believe's that $1fc (burst mode
    (FMODE) register) isn't used in OCS, ECS chips, which it isn't, but
    it is by AGA... ;) 
  

 *  we now turn our AGA copper / display on via the 'cop swap' command




 I suggest you read your manual in regards to custom copper creation. ;)
  
 

 *  To close our screen, all we need to do is firstly turn the Amos copper
    system on, then call a simple procedure which restores the 
    FMODE register to normal, other wise you probably get some rather
    unwanted results.






@ENDNODE



@NODE procs "List of AmosAGA Procedures"


 * The Procedures:
 =================


  Currently AmosAGA is *very* limited in regards to 'custom' AGA
 functions, this will increase as it grows more into custom library.  



  Please Note:  PLEASE BE AWARE THAT ALL INFORMATION PRESENTED IN THESE
                SIMPLE ALPHA PREVIEWS IS COMPLETELY SUBJECT TO CHANGE.




       Proc Name             Inputs           Dizzy
       ---------             ------           -----


   _AGA_SET_PALETTE          [bank]           Loads the current AmosAGA
					      screen with a completely
					      new palette. (256 colours)

					      Bank can either be a bank
                                              number (0->15) or an actual
                                              address.

   _AGA_GET_PALETTE          [bank]	      Bank


   _AGA_SET_COLOUR           [cl,r,g,b]	      Cl = colour number (0->255)
                                               r= Red 
                                               g= green 
                                               b= Blue 


   _AGA_GET_COLOUR           [cl]	      Cl = colour number to read
                                              R,G,B values are returned
                                              in the AGA_R,AGA_G & AGA_B
                                              global variables.





